name: Matthew Sluka
summary: UNLV quarterback Matthew Sluka has left the team amid their undefeated season due to an alleged dispute over name, image, and likeness (NIL) commitments. ESPN reports that the $100,000 NIL deal that Sluka was promised was not fulfilled, leading to his departure. CBS Sports adds that Sluka is citing unfulfilled NIL promises as the reason for his exit from the CFP-hopeful team. The dispute has sparked discussions about the growing tensions in college football's pay-for-play era. Sluka's departure has also drawn comments from LSU coach Brian Kelly, who weighed in on the situation and the impact of NIL on college athletics. The New York Post reports that Sluka's decision to quit in the middle of the season was motivated by a desire for "more money." The situation has highlighted the ongoing challenges and complexities of NIL deals in college sports.

name: Julie Chrisley resentencing
summary: Reality TV star Julie Chrisley, known for the show "Chrisley Knows Best," has been resentenced to seven years in prison for bank fraud and tax evasion. Chrisley was previously sentenced to eight years, but her sentence was reduced upon appeal. During her emotional court appearance, Chrisley apologized for her actions, but the judge upheld the seven-year sentence. The judge also ruled that Chrisley will not be taken into custody by the Federal Bureau of Prisons until after her appeal process is complete. Her daughter, Savannah Chrisley, expressed her fear and concern ahead of her mother's sentencing. Chrisley's prison sentence results from her conviction on charges related to a scheme to defraud banks and evade taxes.
